'''Arise Evans''' (or Rhys or Rice Evans) (1607-1660), was a [[Wales|Welsh]] prophet and fanatic.

==Personal history==
Evans was born about 1607 in Llangelynin parish and was apprenticed to a tailor at Wrexham. While living in Wales he had seen visions and prophetic dreams which were accentuated when he went to London in 1629. In London he made vain efforts to warn [[Charles I of England|King Charles I]] of perceived dangers, but succeeded in telling the [[Robert Devereux, 3rd Earl of Essex|Earl of Essex]] to his face of his future promotions.<ref name="NLoW">{{cite web|url=http://yba.llgc.org.uk/en/s-EVAN-ARI-1607.html |title=Biography of Arise Evans |author=Richards, Thomas |publisher=National Library of Wales|date= |accessdate=1 October 2011}}</ref> Evans became interested in the multifarious sects that flourished under the new liberty of Charles I's reign, opposing most of them, especially the tenets of the [[Fifth Monarchist]].<ref name="NLoW"/> He took particular offence towards  [[Christopher Feake]] and [[William Aspinwall]].<ref name="NLoW"/> 

