{{merge|Mech tribe|discuss=Talk:Mech tribe#Proposed merge with Bodo people|date=April 2018}} {{refimprove|date=July 2017}} {{redirect|Bodos|the Romanian village of Bodoş (Hungarian: Bodos)|Baraolt|umbrella group of ethnic tribes|Bodo-Kachari people}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}} {{Infobox ethnic group | group = Bodo | image = Bodo dance.jpg | image_caption = ''[[Bagurumba]]'', the traditional Bodo dance | population = {{circa|1.5&nbsp;million}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://censusindia.gov.in/Tables_Published/SCST/dh_st_assam.pdf|title=2011 Estimates as per Census report 2001}}</ref> | region1 = | pop1 = | languages = [[Bodo language]] | religions = [[Hindu]], [[Christian]] | related = [[Bodo-Kachari]], [[Bodo-Kachari people|Kachari people]], [[Hajong people]], [[Garo people]],[[Narzary]] | footnotes = | website = }}
The '''Bodos''' ({{IPA-hns|boːɽoː|pron}}) are an [[ethnic]] and linguistic group of the [[Brahmaputra valley]] in the [[Northeast India|northeast]] part of India.
'''Bodo''' Tribe of '''Assam''' - are known to be the '''earliest settlers of Assam''', and the first to cultivate rice and rear silkworms in Assam. The word 'Bodo' has been derived from the word 'Bod' which means Tibet. The Bodos speak the Bodo language.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oknortheast.com/2010/12/bodos-earliest-settlers-of-assam.html|title=Bodos - the Earliest Settlers of Assam|work=OK! North East|access-date=2018-07-31}}</ref>
They are recognized as a plains tribe in the Sixth Schedule of the [[Indian Constitution]]. [[Udalguri]], [[Chirang district|Chirang]], [[Baksa district|Baksa]], [[Sonitpur]], [[Goalpara]], Dhemaji, [[Lakhimpur district|Lakhimpur]], [[Kokrajhar]] of [[Assam]] are considered the centre of the Bodo People. The Bodos living in [[West Bengal]] are called [[Mech tribe|Mech]]. The Bodos use the term ''Bodo's'' (which is pronounced as Borosa meaning son of Bodo's) to describe themselves.
==Language== The [[Bodo language|Boro language]] is one of the languages of the Sino-Tibetan or Tibeto-Chinese speech family. It belongs to the Boro, Naga group of the Assam-Burmese branch of the Sino Tibetan family.
==Religion== <!--[[Hindu Bathouism]] and [[Obonglaoree]] redirect directly here--> {{bar box |title=Religion among Bodos<ref name="census2001">{{citation | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Census of India - Socio-cultural aspects, Table ST-14 | work = | year=2001 | publisher = Government of India, Ministry of Home Affairs}} </ref> |titlebar=#Fcd116 |left1=Religion |right1=Percent |float=right |bars= {{bar percent|[[Hinduism]]|#FF6600|90.31}} {{bar percent|[[Christianity]]|#9955BB|9.40}} {{bar percent|Others|#808080|0.29}} }}
Bodos traditionally practise [[Bathouism]], which is the worshiping of forefathers, known as Obonglaoree. The shijou plant (Euphorbia genus) is taken as the symbol of Bathou and worshiped. It is also claimed as the supreme god. In [[Bodo language]], Ba means five and thou means deep. As Bodos believe in five mighty elements of [[God]], which are Land, Water, Air, Fire and Sky, five has become a significant number in the Bathou religion.
The Shijou tree is encircled with eighteen pairs of designed bamboo sticks and five pairs of ring of bamboo. In front of Shijou within encircled bamboo ring there is a 'Dove Heart'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://udalguri.gov.in/bodo.htm|title=HOME|website=udalguri.gov.in|access-date=2017-04-02}}</ref>
According to the concept of Bathouism, before the creation of universe, there was simply a great void, in which the supreme being 'Aham Guru', Anan Binan Gosai or Obonglaoree existed formlessly. The supreme god Aham guru became tired of living formless existence and desired to live in flesh and blood. He descended on this great void with all human characteristics. Thereafter he created the universe.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Boro Kachari Sonskritir Kinchit Abhas |last=Basumatary |first=Dhuparam |publisher= |year=|isbn= |location=|pages=2–3}}</ref>
==See also== * [[Bodo-Kachari people]] * [[Bodo Sahitya Sabha]] * [[Bodo culture]] * [[Ual (tool)]]
