'''Robert Louis Coble''' (January 22, 1928 &ndash; August 27, 1992) was an American ceramic [[scientist]], notable for his discovery of [[Coble creep]], the effect that carries his name, and for his invention of [[Lucalox]]. <ref name="MIT">[http://tech.mit.edu/V112/N38/coble.38n.html MIT: The Tech-Online Edition; Robert L. Coble, Retired Professor, Dies at 64; Robert L. Coble, a retired professor of materials science and engineering and a widely recognized ceramics researcher.]</ref> <ref name="NAP">[http://www.nap.edu/openbook.php?record_id=4779&page=47 National Academy of Engineering, Memorial Tributes: Volume 7 (1994);ROBERT L. COBLE;BY MERTON C. FLEMINGS]</ref> <ref name="JC">[http://www.lrsm.upenn.edu/~frenchrh/download/9402cobleretrospective.pdf ''Journal of the American Ceramic Society''; Robert L. Coble:A Retrospective]</ref> Coble was a member of the [[National Academy of Engineering]].<ref name="NAP"/><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1978/04/02/archives/engineers-academy-picks-new-members-100-are-chosen-to-join-group.html?sq=%2522Robert%2520L.%2520Coble%2522&scp=1&st=cse ''New York Times'': The National Academy of Engineering yesterday announced the election of 100 engineers to membership in the academy and the election of 19 foreign associates; Robert L. Coble, Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Cambridge, Mass; April 2, 1978.]</ref> The [[National Academy of Engineering]] said that Coble was "widely recognized for his contributions to the theory of [[sintering]] of materials and to ceramic processing".<ref name="NAP"/> Coble received Humboldt Research Award in 1984.<ref name="NAP"/> The [[American Ceramic Society]] established an award in Coble's name: Robert L. Coble Award for Young Scholars.<ref>[http://ceramics.org/acers-community/award-winners-resources American Ceramic Society: Robert L. Coble Award for Young Scholars]</ref>
== Biography== Coble was born in [[Uniontown, Pennsylvania]]. He graduated from [[Bethany College (West Virginia)|Bethany College]] (1950) and received his doctorate from the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (1955). After graduation from MIT, Coble worked as a researcher at the [[General Electric Research Laboratory]]. He Joined MIT faculty in 1960, and became a full professor at [[MIT]] in 1969. Coble retired in 1988 and died by drowning in 1992.
Coble drowned off the coast of the island of Maui in Hawaii on August 27, 1992.<ref name="MIT"/>
